[2026-07-05 05:12:40] nacho: Fixed darwin_cycle.el idle-exit bug (new variant). Root cause: when async tools (execute_code_local, delegate) are running, the darwin cycle's FSM stays in TOOL state, but the tool's subprocess is NOT in gptel--request-alist (it's a plain Emacs process, not a gptel request). The active-requests check found no entries, fell through to the catch-all branch which incremented idle-count, eventually hitting the 1800s safety net and triggering "Idle Exit". Fix: added explicit branch for non-terminal FSM state that resets idle-count to 0 instead of incrementing it. The FSM being in TOOL/WAIT/TRET means work is in progress -- the tool's own timeout handles hangs. Byte-compile clean.
[2026-07-05 06:16:50] nacho: Diagnosed darwin_cycle.el "Idle Exit" regression. Root cause: stale .elc files shadowing fixed .el source. Commit 746bdd9 added a non-terminal FSM branch (setq idle-count 0) to prevent idle-count increment during async tool execution, but the .elc was compiled 2 days earlier (2026-07-03 03:14) and load-prefer-newer was nil (default). Emacs loaded the stale .elc with the old catch-all (cl-incf idle-count) code, causing idle-count to accumulate during every async tool call until the 1800s safety net triggered "Idle Exit". Fix: (1) Deleted all stale .elc files in init.d/ (14 files affected), (2) Added (setq load-prefer-newer t) to init.el to prevent recurrence. This was NOT a reintroduction of the original delegate-tracking bug -- it was a new failure mode: the fix was correct but never loaded.
